messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /printshops/{printShopID}/employees

All HTTP methods acceptable: false

HTTP method availability (based on the controller code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The ManagerController class does not declare a class-level @RequestMapping, so the method-level mappings are the full path.
- The editEmployee method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.PUT) — this defines the endpoint path as /printshops/{printShopID}/employees and explicitly allows PUT.
- The same path is also used by two other methods in the class:
  - getEmployees: @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.GET) → GET allowed.
  - addEmployee: @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.POST) → POST allowed.
- There is a DELETE mapping in the class, but it is for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID} (with the extra {employeeID} path parameter), not for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees; therefore DELETE is not allowed on the exact path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees per the code.
- No method is declared with RequestMethod.HEAD, RequestMethod.OPTIONS, RequestMethod.TRACE, RequestMethod.PATCH, or with no method specified (which would mean all methods). The prompt asked to base acceptability on the code (not runtime framework defaults), so those methods are marked false.
